<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>DDB0336</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Cabinet Office</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> – Supplementary written evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">DEREGULATION BILL – DEVOLUTION PAPER</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> FOR THE JOINT COMMITTEE</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The purpose of this paper is to explain to the Joint Committee the approach which was taken to devolution issues in the context of the draft Deregulation Bill.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Bill makes a large number of repeals, revocations and other amendments to legislation as well as introducing some new provisions. Some provisions do not give rise to any devolution issues; and where devolution issues do arise, they vary for each piece of legislation being changed. So the position in the Bill overall is complex. Individual departments have liaised with the devolved administrations throughout the drafting process in accordance with the Memorandum of Understanding. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Territorial extent and application: general position</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Clause 63 sets out the Bill’s territorial extent. Clause 63(1) provides that, except where specified, any repeal, revocation or other amendment has the same extent as the original legislation. The commentary on each clause and Schedule in the Explanatory Notes explains their extent (the jurisdictions which the provisions form part of the law of) and also their application (if different from their extent.)  Clause 63(2) and (3) specify those areas where the changes being made extend differently from the original legislation. Clause 63(5) provides that certain measures which are being newly introduced form part of the law of England and Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Liaison with the devolved administrations </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Individual departments have taken responsibility for consulting with, and informing, officials in the devolved administrations – often with the involvement of officials in the territorial offices - in relation to those provisions of the Bill which implement policies for which they are responsible. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Communication with the devolved administrations  took place in accordance with the Memorandum of Understanding on Devolution, and included:-</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Keeping the devolved administrations generally informed about developments as a matter of courtesy.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Consultation about whether particular provisions of the Bill deal with devolved matters.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Consulting in relation to clauses where a provision of the Bill implements a policy in a non-devolved area but which might nevertheless affect a devolved area. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Consulting, in relation to provisions which deal with devolved matters, as to whether the relevant devolved administration is content with this and willing to promote a Legislative Consent Motion (‘LCM’) on the introduction of the Bill. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As reflected in paragraph 10 of the Explanatory Notes, at the time that the Bill was published, discussions in relation to the position on LCMs were ongoing in a number of cases. In those cases, the devolved administrations were consulted about whether, pending the outcome of the discussions, they would be content for the Bill, as published in draft for pre-legislative scrutiny, to deal with the devolved matter. The provisions of the Bill dealing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with devolved matters were included only with the agreement of the relevant devolved administration.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The draft Bill was published on 1st July, and officially shared, in its entirety, with all of the devolved administrations at that point.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Current work on devolution aspects </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As indicated, some provisions in the Bill deal with matters which fall within the legislative competence of one or more of the devolved legislatures.  LCMs will therefore need to be sought if those provisions are included in the Bill as introduced.  It is envisaged that, in order to facilitate this  process,  each devolved administration will seek a single ‘portmanteau’ LCM for the Bill as a whole, and that this will be centrally co-ordinated. Points of contact have been identified in each devolved administration.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Discussions with officials in the devolved administrations about whether an LCM is required in relation to particular clauses are ongoing.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">CABINET OFFICE </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">14</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; font-weight:bold; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>